I started investigating 3D printing in late 2014, I knew I had to be able to cerate my own designs so my first task was selecting a CAD program. I selected ViaCad 2D/3D starting with v8. I spend two years learning to use this program when I had some time to get to it. I upgraded to v9 then v10 with ProPack and have never regretted my choice. This is an incredible and underrated CAD program. There are many videos available available on how to use it. The manual for v10 is great (the previous manuals were less so) and one their is a fantastic hints and tips book that I highly recommend anyone get with it.

My first printer kit was a Wilson TS. Instead of just assembling and using it I read far to=o many articles on modifications and ordered many "improved parts" and tried to change too many items on it before I had it completed. It is still not yet finished yet, LOL.

Once I felt good with the CAD program and had created a fer designs (STL files) that I had local people print for me, I bought a Creality Ender 2 that I assembled and used perfectly for fou three months months. I then wanted to do some larger items and bought an JGAurora A5. It assembled instantly and like the Ender 2 it worked perfectly out of the box! I've used them both now for a year and and very please with it in virtually every regard. It does not have auto bed leveling but their "leveling assist" make leveling a 2 minute task and I surely do not need to do it but every third print.

Wanting US made filament I have purchased Push Plastic 95% of the time. Their filament prints perfectly on both printers and their colors are simply clean and sharp. I have bought five spools of PLA from Microcenter locally. It is also decent but simply not quite as good as the Push. For example, their yellow is a sort of milky version of that color and the red spool I bought there had the bottom layer stick to the bed but then broke off after that tip layer. I need to play with it to see if higher or lower temps in either the bed of extruder can solve that unpleasant trait on that particular spool. Again, the Push plastic had not given me any such concerns.

I print a lot of home storage gadgets. We have a small home and these like shaver hangers for the bathrooms have really helped. The items I design then print have mostly been the same sort of storage or organizational pieces. I have a plethora of battery powered items and Arduino projects and have designed and printed racks, brackets, and such and they are really handy to have round.

I got into 3d Printing because I like mechanical things and the mechanics of the machines intrigued me. My first 3D printer was the Monoprice Maker Select V2 followed quickly by an FLSun Kossel Delta and a Monoprice Select Mini. The Kossel was especially fun in that I had to build it myself, from which I learned a lot. I've since built two other FLSun Kossels using parts I printed myself and a Sculptr Delta, again using parts I've modified myself. I am also working on making an M-Prime One cartesian printer, again with parts I've been modifying.

My designs, thus far, have been in the area of modifying current designs to better suit my personal needs rather than making anything truly new. I do have some new things in the works for the M Prime build, but these are simplistic in design. I'm more the "engineer" type than the "designer" type.

Retired design engineer that was a NERD before it was 'trendy.' My work experience was doing new product development (including system level and detailed design work) within the medical electronics, laboratory instrumentation, and advanced water treatment system fields.

Many of my models are currently unprinted and untested since I've been doing long-term maintenance on my old printer, but I have shared them anyway to generate both inspiration and feedback. Now that I've got my Prusa i3 Mk3 up and running, I'm in the process of testing them out. My favorite artistic design so far is the snowflake Christmas light collection, while my favorite practical design is the AA Battery Holder. Please print and modify anything you'd like, and ask any questions you might. Let's make some things!

First off, everything designed here was done using Fusion 360. I say that in hopes that they won't take away my free use of the program and I can continue to make all kinds of stuff.

These are a small portion of what I have done. As you see I don't spend anytime at all on the presentation and it's quite simple why. I expect no reward in any way for what I share so the time spent making the creation look pretty is taking away from my next creation that someone might find usable.

I don't spend anytime telling you how to print it unless it not obvious. Once again, trying to spend time doing something else to share.

All of these creations I have made are for my own use. I don't make creations to post unless I have a use for them. This is probably 30 percent of what I've made. Some are too good and would be stolen, some are so bad or so simple that I'd be embarrassed to share them. I have noticed that some of the designs that took minutes to create are fairly popular so I'm opening my window up a little as what to share.

I started making things 50 years ago, I've been doing CNC for about 30 years but it's only the last ten years that the software,materials and equipment have come together so just about anyone can be a productive maker.

Enjoy what's here.

Cheers

3D printing was a dream come true for me, I have always been a creator of things in my mind, and now I finally have the tool to make my ideas a reality. I started building Defiant in November 2013, a RepStrap of my own design, using the reprap wiki and blogs to learn the bits that I did not know. January, 2014, I melted my first plastic with it. I made a few decent parts over the next few months with it and began realizing the flaws of my designs. I was able to make enough parts to upgrade the performance, and now am working on designing the parts for my next printer, that when released will be an official RepRap. I named my first printer Defiant because I had to defy everything to make it happen. financial rules, laws of physics, time constraints, and most of all, my wife. these are not easy obstacles to overcome... but nothing could stop me from getting here.
